1. Introduction
Some universities including Augustana University allow the majority of their
students(Especially one’s living on campus) to utilize the central mailing address for the school to
receive all mail, and later distribute the mail to each student based on the box number they own.
But right now, the distribution system is not efﬁcient. Important mails may not be retrieved
for months just because the student who received the mail is not notiﬁed on arrival. Students
have to repeatedly, or regularly check their box in order to not miss important mails.
But that should not be the case in today’s world of automated systems. And this is exactly
the problem what this web application is supposed to ﬁx. This web app gives the postmaster of
the schools access to a database that stores new mail arrivals as records. Students then can use a
properly designed and implemented website to access the database in an efﬁcient manner. Future
implementations may include students setting their accounts to “push” access instead of a “pull”,
so that they can receive notiﬁcations for new mail even without even checking the site. But even
with the current “pull” access (checking the website for update themselves just by logging on), the
major drawback of the existing system (which is taking a trip to the physical mailbox) is solved.
2. Technologies used
Database - Mongodb
Server side - Node.js(server side javascript)
Front End - HTML(EJS template), CSS and JS(client side)

2.2. Server Side
Node.js is used for server side design. Node handles all the routes using express,
authenticates users(students) using passport and Google OAuth 2.0, and ﬁnally renders all
the templates to HTML using EJS. Here are some dependencies(Modules) I mainly used:
• Express & EJS - routing and templating
!3
“Users” collection
“Mails” collection
• Passport and Google OAuth - authentication by using google APIs(It limits access
to email domains with @ole.augie.edu- Augustana students)
• Mongoose - connecting to the Mongodb server. MLab’s connection to Mongoose
is as simple as pasting a link.
2.3. Front End
Front end gets rendered to HTML using EJS. Express also assigns a speciﬁc folder for
all the static JS, CSS and Image ﬁles called “public”.
A. Bootstrap
✦
Majority of the site uses bootstrap css and js as a front end framework.
✦
It helps in great deal to make the site responsive(Fluid layout and overall
design to make the site user friendly across many devices; including
Smartphones, tablets and desktops)
✦
It also includes pre-deﬁned classes to make the styling of forms, buttons
and other HTML elements easy and at the same time responsive(see above
bullet point).
B. EJS
✦
Although it’s a Node.js feature, it has more to do with the front end
programming of the side than it has to do with the server side.
✦
It connects the server side to the client side(front end).
✦
Unlike HTML, it uses partials to only code repetitive page structures
once(like headers, footers), and render them multiple times dynamically.
!4

4. Features not included in this version
• https protocol - for more robust overall security of the site. Plus it prevents network
snifﬁng apps from prying over GET and POST requests
• handle redirect codes - I’ve setup some redirect codes for displaying correct error
messages, successful logout messages and for more overall user friendliness (like when a
user tries to access a page without signing in…)
• leaﬂet to visually track packages - display where a certain package has been, current
routes, and more tracking related data
• Admin Access to add and modify records - instead of a postmaster directly accessing a
database, having a separate Admin site to add and modify records easily and in an
efﬁcient manner.
